<div id="review_183587118" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/183587118" />
    <a title="Gordon Doherty" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5253742-gordon-doherty"><img alt="Gordon Doherty" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1457200082p2/5253742.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/183587118?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gordon Doherty" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gordon Doherty" href="/user/show/5253742-gordon-doherty">Gordon Doherty</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer183587118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5891472503675309131">If I ever forget what good storytelling is, then I can safely turn to David Gemmell for a sterling reminder. <br/><br/><br/>Sword in the Storm exhibits all the traits that made me love his style (have read Troy series, Lion of Macedon series, Stones of Power series) and in particular the very real-feeling portrayal of Connovar, the flawed hero. Every character has a touch of this, no archetypal villains or infallible good guys in this story, and the people of the Roman/Kelt-like world only become tainted as go</span>
  <span id="freeText5891472503675309131" style="display:none">If I ever forget what good storytelling is, then I can safely turn to David Gemmell for a sterling reminder. <br /><br /><br />Sword in the Storm exhibits all the traits that made me love his style (have read Troy series, Lion of Macedon series, Stones of Power series) and in particular the very real-feeling portrayal of Connovar, the flawed hero. Every character has a touch of this, no archetypal villains or infallible good guys in this story, and the people of the Roman/Kelt-like world only become tainted as good or bad because of their choices and actions.<br /><br />Sword in the Storm is the first in the Rigante series and it's a safe bet that I'll be reading the rest after this masterpiece.<br /><br />If you're a historical fiction fan, don't let the fantasy aspect put you off. This book is a must read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5891472503675309131" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


